he potential to meet its original promises. Based on nearly a decade of pioneering research, After the Gig dives into what went wrong along the way to this contemporary reimagining of labor. The book examines multiple types of data from thirteen cases to identify the unique features and potential of sharing platforms that prior research has failed to identify. Juliet B. Schor presents a compelling case that we can engineer a reboot: through regulatory reforms and cooperative platforms owned and controlled by users, an equitable and actual sharing economy is still possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCooperation. 0aPrecarious employmentxCase studies. 0aSelf-employedxCase studies. 0aSharingxEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh  acase studies on gig work.  aenvironmental degradation.  agentrification.  ahow to fix the sharing economy.  alabor market changes.  anew workforce.  asolutions to our broken system.  astructural racism.  atech corruption.  aurban futures.  awhy is taking an uber or lyft bad.  awork inequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2020 Englishz978311070479208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2020z9783110704624oZDB-23-DBV08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520974227zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520974227.jpg  a978-3-11-069041-5  UC Press